- VSCode Version: 1.9.1
- OS Version: 10.11.6

Is there a way to show my custom suggestion every key input using provideCompletionItems?
Suggestion is not always displayed.

- My extension code.

``` typescript
'use strict';

import { languages, TextDocument, ExtensionContext, CompletionItem, Position } from 'vscode';

export function activate(context: ExtensionContext) {
    context.subscriptions.push(languages.registerCompletionItemProvider('*', {
        provideCompletionItems(document: TextDocument, position: Position) {
            return [new CompletionItem('hello world')];
        }
    }));
}
```

Suggestion test in `test.ts`

- case 1. input `h` => `hello world ` is not displayed.
![2017-02-19 11 17 08](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/10220449/23098581/054f1036-f695-11e6-9479-7463238f30d7.png)

- case 2. input `let h` => `hello world` is displayed.
![2017-02-19 11 18 17](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/10220449/23098585/24fc7414-f695-11e6-8964-5e5234e453e7.png)

- case 3. input `let h = h` => `hello world ` is not displayed.
![2017-02-19 11 19 19](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/10220449/23098587/4b6450cc-f695-11e6-82ee-02fd0af363c1.png)

I want to show my custom suggestion in every case.
But above case1 and case3 is not called  `provideCompletionItems`

Thanks

- VSCode Version: `1.9.1`
- OS Version: `Windows 10`

Steps to Reproduce:

Run the following extension:

```
export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
    vscode.workspace.onDidCloseTextDocument((event) => {
        console.log("Closed document: " + event.fileName);
        console.log("Visible documents:");
        vscode.window.visibleTextEditors.forEach((editor) => {
            if (editor.document) {
                if (editor.document.fileName == event.fileName) {
                    console.warn(editor.document.fileName);
                }
                else {
                    console.log(editor.document.fileName);
                }
            }
        })
    });
}
```

1. In the VSCode editor being debugged, open many files.
2. Drag one of the files into split view
3. Focus the right editor panel
4. Close a file in the left panel, without giving it focus (click the x, just don't click the document first)
5. When the file is closed in the left panel, a new file takes its place
6. But `visibleTextEditors` will return the closed file, not the new file
7. This situation continues until the new file gains focus

Took me ages to figure out how to reproduce this, I hope its not as designed.
